title: For Sale:  Bersa BP9CC package
postcontent: I bought this Bersa BP9cc 9mm pistol in February of this year. I eventually got to take it to the gun range and really liked how it felt and how accurately it shot. I also liked the trigger, although it was lighter and with a shorter reset than I had experienced on any of my previous semi-automatic pistols.I did have some light primer strikes, which I did not like. I took it back out to the range a few days later and had some additional light primer strikes. I contacted the Bersa distributor and they responded immediately. They were very helpful and provided an authorized warranty center contact. I called them and explained the issue of light primer strikes. The gunsmith asked me for the serial number and, as I started reading it to him, told me that those serial numbers came with a different firing pin and spring than the later serial numbers.The gunsmith told me to send the gun to him and he would replace those parts, inspect and ensure the gun is fully functional, and clean and return it to me. I received the gun back last week and they had replaced the firing pin and spring. I had a chance to take it to the range late yesterday afternoon and put 100 rounds of a combination of Federal and Perfecta FMJ 115 grain ammo through the gun. I didn't have a single light primer strike or any other issue.This Bersa doesn't have a safety and I don't believe at this time I will be carrying a conceal gun without one (just a personal choice) so I am selling it. It does have a internal locking system on the right side of the slide operated by the included Bersa key that enables you to prevent the gun from firing if you prefer for household safety, but I never had a need to utilize that feature.Sale includes everything you see in the pictures, plus assorted parts the distributor sent me at my request in lieu of reimbursing me for shipping charges to the gunsmith. Those parts include a new firing pin assembly and recoil spring guide assembly. This is a great price on a really nice single-stack 9mm."Must be able to complete at this time a local face-to-face cash sale. Buyer must be at least 21, Oklahoma resident able to legally buy a firearm in Oklahoma, and must have a current valid Oklahoma issued picture ID. No exceptions."
